%h3=help.name(cookies[:setting])
%p
  You must
  -if subtype.more?
    #{display(subtype.solution)} <em>after</em> you have #{display(subtype.role).en}</em>.
  -else
    #{display(subtype.herring)} <em>before</em> you #{display(subtype.problem)}.
%p
  -if subtype.more?
    Make sure you  #{display(subtype.solution)} in the #{help.time}, as it is difficult to #{display(subtype.solution)} in the #{help.flip.time} unless you are #{subtype.sick}.
  -else
    Try to postpone #{display(subtype.problem).ing} until #{help.after.time}.

-if @subtype
  %p
    -if subtype.more?
      It is also possible to #{display(subtype.solution)} in the #{help.after.after.time} (a natural time to #{display(subtype.help.opposite)}) or the #{help.season}, when you are in the mood to #{display(help)} things and thus donâ€™t feel the urge to #{display(subtype.role)}.
    -else
      You may also #{display(subtype.herring)} in the #{help.after.after.time} during the #{help.season}, or whenever you feel like #{display(transform(help, :ing))} things, in which case you can #{display(subtype.problem)} more afterwards.
  %p
    Just remember that you must
    -if subtype.more?
      <em>#{display(subtype.solution)}</em> whenever you have finished #{display(transform(subtype.role, :ing))}.
    -else
      not #{display(subtype.problem)} until <em>after</em> you have #{display(subtype.herring).en}.

-if @type
  =link_to 'more', subtype_path(subtype.symbol)
